title What Glow and Rye share under the hood -- the three-hop bridge
prompt we will have to write and silo how and what Glow and Rye are going to share under the hood
think Recognized this as filling a real gap rather than deciding something new: two documents already landed this session (the active-reviving decision, the sameness-and-the-rune brief) both assumed Glow and Rye share something under the hood -- one said "Hoon-flavoured runes compiling to bounded Rye/RISC-V," the other said "written by hand in the Rye a rune's expansion would generate automatically" and named "the same Rye-to-Zig-to-RISC-V pipeline" -- yet neither had ever stated the mechanics as its own explicit decision. The task was gathering, not inventing.
think Chose to verify Rye's own real mechanism before proposing anything for Glow, rather than assume how "Rye is a thin frontend on Zig" actually works day to day. Read rye/README.md and rye/src/main.rye directly rather than relying on the phrase alone.
think The real finding surprised the initial hypothesis in one respect: Rye's own bridge does not do any real parsing or transpilation at all -- bridge_to_zig and rewrite_rye_imports perform exactly one textual transformation (rewriting the .rye suffix to .zig inside @import(...) calls), and every other byte of the file passes through completely unchanged. Rye's "front-end" is a file-extension and import-path bridge, nothing more; every real capability is Zig's, inherited whole.
think This finding sharpened the design rather than complicating it: since Glow's own rune syntax is real new punctuation (not valid Zig text Rye's existing bridge could pass through), Glow needs the one thing Rye has never needed -- an actual parser -- but that parser's OWN job is narrow: emit valid .rye text, then hand off to Rye's existing, completely unchanged bridge. A three-hop pipeline (.glow -> .rye -> .zig -> target) where each hop owns exactly one concern and none re-implements the layer below it.
think Grounded the worked example in already-real code rather than inventing a plausible-looking snippet: the generated-Rye shape shown is drawn directly from glow/rune_bounded_trap.rye's own run_bounded() and linengrow/neth_sim.rye's own hand-written loop, both already green this session -- so the claim "this is what a rune would generate" is illustrated by code that already exists and already runs, not merely asserted as plausible.
think Built the shared-vs-owned split as two parallel tables rather than prose, each entry paired with a one-line "why" tracing back to an already-seated fact from this session (TAME's bounds, the nine-piece riscv64 proof, the value-model distinction from Nock's own noun representation) -- so the split reads as derived, not asserted.
think Checked the silo question deliberately rather than assuming: is "Zig" nameable directly in active-designing, given the silo principle's own explicit list (TAME, Aurora, Rye, Brix, ... RISC-V) does not literally include it? Found clear, repeated precedent across this session's own already-landed active-designing briefs (the revival decision, the sameness-and-the-rune brief itself) naming "Zig" freely, alongside RISC-V, as foundational infrastructure this project builds upon rather than an inspiration drawn from elsewhere -- followed that established convention rather than introducing a new one.
obs The most useful outcome of actually reading Rye's own source before writing anything was narrowing the design, not expanding it: had I assumed Rye's bridge did "some reasonable transpilation," I might have proposed Glow needing to duplicate or extend that transpilation logic. Because it does nothing but import-path rewriting, Glow's own job is cleanly separable and genuinely smaller than it might have seemed -- one parser, emitting text, done.
file active-designing/20260716-093000_glow-and-rye-what-shares-under-the-hood.md new -- the three-hop bridge, the shared/owned tables, a worked example drawn from real code
file active-designing/README.md new index row
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md checked line naming the brief; Last-updated re-stamped
recommend check-in for whether to actually start building the .glow parser and lowering pass -- this brief names the shape but writes no parser; building one would be squarely in the same "genuinely new design territory" register as the Hoon-to-Nock compiler front end named twice already this session, and deserves the same kind of explicit go-ahead before starting rather than a direct continuation.
